 7 SPECIALCASES
 7.1 Natural vs. Synthetic Distinction
 7.1.1 Natural compounds tend to score higher because:
 ‚Ä¢ Evolved alongside water-based biology
 ‚Ä¢ Typically rich in‚ÄìOH,‚ÄìO‚Äì,‚ÄìNH groups
 ‚Ä¢ Compatible timescale dynamics
 ‚Ä¢ Example: Betanin (1.0), Stevia (0.8‚Äì0.9)
 7.1.2 Synthetic compounds often score lower because:
 ‚Ä¢ Designed for physical properties, not biocompatibility
 ‚Ä¢ Often contain sulfonate/sulfate for stability
 ‚Ä¢ Mayhavepolymer structures with wrong dynamics
 ‚Ä¢ Example: Polysorbate 80 (0.3‚Äì0.4), Azo dyes (0.3‚Äì0.35)
 7.1.3 Exception
 Some natural compounds score poorly:
 ‚Ä¢ Carrageenan (natural but sulfated polymer)
 ‚Ä¢ Showsstructure matters more than origin
 7.2 Dose-Dependency Prediction
 7.2.1 BCS0.55‚Äì0.69 (BORDERLINE)
 ‚Ä¢ Safe at low, infrequent doses
 ‚Ä¢ Problems emerge with chronic high exposure
 ‚Ä¢ Example: Sodium benzoate (GRAS but chronic exposure ‚Üí issues)
 7.2.2 BCS0.25‚Äì0.54 (POOR/MODERATE)
 ‚Ä¢ Dose-response curve steep
 ‚Ä¢ Evenmoderate doses show effects
 ‚Ä¢ Avoid chronic exposure
 ‚Ä¢ Example: Aspartame (safe at ADI, but concerns exist)
CODEX BCS ALGORITHM
 15
 7.2.3 BCS< 0.25 (VERYPOOR)
 ‚Ä¢ Nosafedose for chronic exposure
 ‚Ä¢ Evenlowdoses disrupt biology
 ‚Ä¢ Should be banned/severely restricted
 ‚Ä¢ Example: Erythrosine (banned despite ‚Äúsafe‚Äù ADI)
 7.3 Metabolite Consideration
 Important: BCS score should also consider metabolites!
 7.3.1 Example: Aspartame
 ‚Ä¢ Parent compound BCS ‚àº0.5‚Äì0.6
 ‚Ä¢ Metabolizes to: phenylalanine, aspartic acid, methanol
 ‚Ä¢ Phenylalanine accumulation in PKU patients = contraindication
 ‚Ä¢ Methanol ‚Üíformaldehyde (though amounts small)
 Rule: If metabolites are more problematic than parent, use LOWER of the two BCS
 scores for safety assessment.
